Therefore, the answer should be \boxed{1.376 \times 10^9} atoms/m. **Final Answer** The linear density of atoms along the $<110>$ directions in barium is \boxed{1.376 \times 10^9} atoms per meter. </think> To determine the linear density of atoms along the $<110>$ directions in barium (Ba), we start by noting that barium has a body-centered cubic (BCC) structure. The key steps are as follows: 1. **Atomic Radius and Lattice Parameter**: - The atomic radius \( r \) of barium is approximately 222 pm. - The lattice parameter \( a \) for a BCC structure is given by \( a = \frac{4r}{\sqrt{3}} \). - Substituting \( r = 222 \) pm, we get: \[ a = \frac{4 \times 222}{\sqrt{3}} \approx \frac{888}{1.732} \approx 513.3 \text{ pm} \] 2. **Length of the <110> Direction**: - The length of the $<110>$ direction (a face diagonal) in the unit cell is \( a\sqrt{2} \). - Substituting \( a = 513.3 \) pm, we get: \[ \text{Length} = 513.3 \times \sqrt{2} \approx 513.3 \times 1.414 \approx 725.2 \text{ pm} \] 3. **Linear Density Calculation**: - The linear density is the number of atoms per unit length along the $<110>$ direction. - In the BCC structure, there is one atom at the corner of the unit cell along the $<110>$ direction. - Therefore, the linear density \( \text{LD} \) is: \[ \text{LD} = \frac{1}{\text{Length}} = \frac{1}{725.2 \text{ pm}} \approx \frac{1}{725.2 \times 10^{-12} \text{ m}} \approx 1.376 \times 10^9 \text{ atoms/m} \] Thus, the linear density of atoms along the $<110>$ directions in barium is \boxed{1.376 \times 10^9} atoms per meter.
